<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-title">Anchor question</div>
  How do you build for a planet that occasionally tries to destroy what you've built?
</div>

<div class="prose">
  <p>Across five weeks (twelve 80-minute blocks), you investigate plate tectonics not as a textbook diagram but as a working theory with real engineering consequences. The unit is anchored on the <a href="/units/unit-3/tectonic-city-builder/">Tectonic City Builder</a> — a custom simulator where you plan and build cities on real plate boundaries (Tōhoku, Anatolian/Istanbul, Merapi, Cascadia, Hawaii), spend a fixed budget on housing and engineering technologies, and learn which decisions saved lives when the simulation runs the real disaster.</p>
  <p>The simulator is paired with primary-source case studies — Tōhoku 2011, Kobe 1995, Sumatra-Andaman 2004, Pinatubo 1991, Pompeii 79 CE. You don't memorise these. You use them as evidence to defend your engineering choices.</p>
</div>

